 sharp rise in air temperatures show that climate change is in full effect – and may be outstripping predictions.</p><p><br />The numbers are in, and they are unforgiving: 2015 was the hottest year on record, and it wasn’t even close. The announcement was expected—scientists monitoring global temperatures predicted before the end of the year that 2015 would set a record for warmth, in part because of the massive El Niño event currently under way in the Pacific Ocean. But the data released today confirm that human-induced global warming is pushing temperatures higher at an alarming rate: 2014 was the previous record holder for global average surface temperature, clocking in at 0.57 °C above the 1960 to 1990 average, but last year was 0.75 °C above that average.</p>";s:7:"pubdate";s:31:"Wed, 20 Jan 2016 22:05:00 +0000";s:4:"guid";s:104:"http://www.technologyreview.com/news/545791/2015-was-the-warmest-year-on-record-and-it-wasnt-even-close/";s:7:"summary";s:806:"<p>Warming oceans and a sharp rise in air temperatures show that climate change is in full effect – and may be outstripping predictions.</p><p><br />The numbers are in, and they are unforgiving: 2015 was the hottest year on record, and it wasn’t even close. The announcement was expected—scientists monitoring global temperatures predicted before the end of the year that 2015 would set a record for warmth, in part because of the massive El Niño event currently under way in the Pacific Ocean. But the data released today confirm that human-induced global warming is pushing temperatures higher at an alarming rate: 2014 was the previous record holder for global average surface temperature, clocking in at 0.57 °C above the 1960 to 1990 average, but last year was 0.75 °C above that average.</p>";}i:2;a:6:{s:5:"title";s:38:"Don’t Blame Watson for IBM’s Slide";s:4:"link";s:77:"http://www.technologyreview.com/view/545801/dont-blame-watson-for-ibms-slide/";s:11:"description";s:1243:"<p>IBM might be overhyping the AI engine